article.description:
Travis Best's explosive finish led the Miami 
Heat to their best offensive game of the season.
article.headline: Best at his best in overtime as Heat prevail
article.linkText: Heat score 21 points in overtime to sink Suns
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Travis Best was perfect in overtime -- after a nearly imperfect performance in regulation.
Best

Best made a tying layup with 37 seconds left in regulation, then added three baskets in overtime, leading the Miami Heat over the Phoenix Suns 100-90 Monday night. After missing his first nine field-goal attempts of the game, Best made five shots in a row to boost the Heat. ''Travis was great in overtime,'' Miami coach Pat Riley said. In the extra period, Best made all three of his field goal attempts, including two 3-pointers, and both his free throw tries. He opened the overtime with a 3-pointer for an 82-79 lead and followed that with a driving layup. He capped his late-game field goal splurge with another 3, giving him the only three field goals for Miami in the extra period. ''I was going to keep putting them up and eventually I thought they would go down,'' Best said. ''I kept getting good looks (earlier), even when they were defending me. I had taken a couple (of shots) and they missed.'' The rest of the Heat's 21 points in the extra period -- their most ever in a first overtime -- came on foul shots. Best finished with 16 points. Eddie Jones led Miami with 21 points, rookie Caron Butler had 20 and Brian Grant had 17 points and 17 rebounds. Miami scored its final 12 points on free throws, six by Grant, as the Suns fouled desperately in an effort to catch up. The Heat finished 27-of-31 from the foul line, while Phoenix was 11-of-12. The Heat also outrebounded the Suns 49-35. Shawn Marion topped the Suns with a season-high 30 points, rookie Amare Stoudemire had a season-high 20 points, and Stephon Marbury scored 18. Marion and Stoudemire each had nine rebounds. Another key to the game was Miami going to a zone defense, after the Suns had opened a 13-point lead in the third quarter. ''The zone helped us,'' Riley said. ''It's the first time in my career that I played a zone. We caught them a little by surprise with it. We've been working hard on it in practice and tonight we decided to use it. I was almost embarrassed to call it.'' Phoenix coach Frank Johnson conceded that the zone hurt the Suns. ''We went from shooting 50 percent in the first half to 40 for the game, and that zone really hurt us,'' he said. ''We became hesitant with our shots and our ball movement. I guess Pat Riley won't be embarrassed to call it anymore after tonight.'' For a team not noted for its accuracy, the Suns were very proficient in the first half, connecting on 51.3 percent of their shots (20-for-39) in building a 44-41 lead at the break. Coming into the game, Phoenix ranked 27th in the league in field goal percentage (.401). The Heat stayed close because of their rebounding. They outrebounded the Suns 23-13, including 12 off the offensive glass, and had 17 second-chance points to only two for Phoenix. Grant had nearly as many rebounds as the Suns with 11 at halftime. Jones gave the Heat their biggest lead in regulation, 53-48, by scoring 10 consecutive points, including two 3-pointers, early in the third period. After the teams traded baskets, the Suns reeled off 18 straight points, highlighted by 3-pointers by Marion and Penny Hardaway, for a 68-55 lead. Miami responded with the final eight points of the quarter, five by James, cutting Phoenix's lead to 68-63. The Heat continued their run in the fourth quarter and finally went ahead 75-73 on two free throws by Butler with 4:37 left, capping a 20-5 run. Game notes
Marbury was chosen Western Conference Player of the Week after averaging 24.5 points, including a team-high 43 against San Antonio, 8.0 assists and 2.8 steals in four games last week. ... Butler was selected Eastern Conference Rookie of the Month for November _ the first Miami player ever to receive the honor. He averaged 12.7 points, 5.9 rebounds, 2.5 assists and a team-leading 1.38 steals in 16 games. ... Marion had to be assisted off the court with 7:23 left in the second quarter after injuring his left ankle while jumping for an offensive rebound. But he returned less than five minutes later. ... It was the first time this season the Heat reached 100 points. ... This was the first of a four-game West Coast trip for the Heat. Their other stops are against the Los Angeles Clippers, Portland and Seattle.
